<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-27T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-27T14:00:00-05:00" n="425" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.30/1: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Smith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-27T14:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">October 27,
                                        1919—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 28—4
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Legation’s October 22, 10 a.m.<note n="19" xml:id="d425fn19">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <p>President today asked me to ascertain if my Government would permit naval
                            commission come to Peru for the purpose of directing and reorganizing
                            Peruvian Navy.</p>
                        <pb facs="0468" n="368" xml:id="pg_368"/>
                        <p>Also brought up the question of United States furnishing Marine police
                            for Callao. He stated that Foreign Office would, within short time, make
                            official request for above mentioned services.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>